Clustering Heatmap - RNA-Seq

CCDL for ALSF

Purpose: This notebook illustrates one way that you can use harmonized data from refine.bio in downstream analyses.

TODO: This introduction section will be revamped when the intro to an example analysis (#122: https://github.com/AlexsLemonade/refinebio-examples/pull/122) gets more polished/determined.

0.1 Install libraries

This script uses the R package DESeq2 for normalization and the R package pheatmap for clustering and creating a heatmap.
Citation: Love, M.I., Huber, W., Anders, S. Moderated estimation of fold change and dispersion for RNA-Seq data with DESeq2 Genome Biology 15(12):550 (2014)
Citation: Raivo Kolde (2019). pheatmap: Pretty Heatmaps. R package version 1.0.12. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=pheatmap

if (!("pheatmap" %in% installed.packages())) {
  # Install pheatmap
  install.packages("pheatmap", update = FALSE)
}

if (!("DESeq2" %in% installed.packages())) {
  # Install DESeq2
  BiocManager::install("DESeq2", update = FALSE)
}

Attach the pheatmap and DESeq2 libraries:

# Attach the `pheatmap` library
library(pheatmap)

# Attach the `DESeq2` library
library(DESeq2)

# Magrittr pipe
`%>%` <- dplyr::`%>%`

# Set the seed so our results are reproducible:
set.seed(12345)

We are going to need an output folder for our heatmaps. Lets create an output plots directory.

# Define the file path to the plots directory
plots_dir <- "plots" # Replace with path to desired output plots directory

# Create the plots folder if it doesn't exist
if (!dir.exists(plots_dir)) {
  dir.create(plots_dir)
}

0.2 Import and set up data

Data downloaded from refine.bio include a metadata [tab separated values (tsv)] (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tab-separated_values) file and a data tsv file. This chunk of code will read the both tsv files and add them as data.frame objects to your environment.

The data that we downloaded from refine.bio for this analysis has 19 samples (obtained from 19 mice with acute myeloid leukemia (AML)), containing RNA-sequencing results for types of AML under controlled treatment conditions.

0.3 How are our samples clustering together?

0.3.1 Create a DESeqDataset

We will be using the DESeq2 package for normalization, which requires us to format our data into a DESeqDataSet object. We turn the data.frame (or matrix) into a DESeqDataSet object and specify which variable labels our experimental groups using the design argument.

# The `DESeqDataSetFromMatrix` function needs the values to be converted to
# integers
df <- df %>%
  # Mutate numeric variables to be integers
  dplyr::mutate_if(is.numeric, round)

# Create a `DESeqDataSet` object
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(
  countData = df, # This is the data.frame with the counts values for all replicates in our dataset
  colData = metadata, # This is the data.frame with the annotation data for the replicates in the counts data.frame
  design = ~ refinebio_treatment # Replace with an appropriate design variable for your analysis
)

0.3.2 Define a minimum counts cutoff

We want to filter out the genes that have not been expressed or that have low expression counts because we want to remove any possible noise from our data before we normalize the data and create our heatmap. We are going to do some pre-filtering to keep only genes with 10 or more reads total. Note that rows represent gene data and the columns represent sample data in our dataset.

# Let's take a look at the distribution of counts first

# Sum up the counts for each gene -- which means we want the sum of counts for
# each row as the rows represent gene data and the columns represent sample data
# in our dataset
count_sums <- data.frame(count = rowSums(counts(dds)))

# Create a density plot using the sums
ggplot2::ggplot(count_sums, ggplot2::aes(x = count)) +
  ggplot2::geom_density() +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(ggplot2::aes(xintercept = 10), # This line represents the current cutoff of 10
                      color = "blue",
                      linetype = "dashed") +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(ggplot2::aes(xintercept = mean(count)), # This line represents the mean count value
                                   color = "red",
                                   linetype = "dashed")

# Define a minimum counts cutoff and filter `DESeqDataSet` object to include
# only rows that have counts above the cutoff
genes_to_keep <- rowSums(counts(dds)) >= 10
dds <- dds[genes_to_keep, ]

0.3.3 Perform DESeq2 normalization

We are going to use the rlog function from the DESeq2 package to normalize the data. TODO: Add a note/link to section in documentation on why we use rlog vs vst and normTransform.

# Normalize the data in the `DESeqDataSet` object using the
# `rlog` function from the `DESEq2` R package
dds_norm <- rlog(dds)

0.3.4 Choose genes of interest

Although you may want to create a heatmap including all of the genes in the set, alternatively, the heatmap could be created using only genes of interest. For this example, we will sort genes by variance, but there are many alternative criterion by which you may want to sort your genes eg fold change, t-statistic, membership to a particular gene ontology, so on.

# Calculate the variance for each gene
variances <- apply(assay(dds_norm), 1, var)

# Determine the upper quartile variance cutoff value
upper_var <- quantile(variances, 0.75)

# Subset the data choosing only genes whose variances are in the upper quartile
df_by_var <- data.frame(assay(dds_norm)) %>%
  dplyr::filter(variances > upper_var)

0.3.5 Create a heatmap

To further customize the heatmap, see a vignette for a guide at this link.

# Create and store the technical replicates heatmap object
pheatmap <-
  pheatmap(
    df_by_var,
    cluster_rows = FALSE, # Replace with `TRUE` to cluster heatmap by rows (genes in this case)
    cluster_cols = FALSE, # Replace with `TRUE` to cluster heatmap by columns (samples in this case)
    main = "Heatmap",
    colorRampPalette(c("deepskyblue",
                       "black",
                       "yellow"))(25
                       ),
    scale = "row" # Scale values in the direction of genes (rows)
  )

Now lets add some annotation bars to our heatmap.

0.3.6 Add annotation bars

We are going to manipulate the metadata and add variables with the information that we would like to use to annotate the heatmap.

# Let's prepare the annotation data.frame for the uncollapsed `DESeqData` set
# object which will be used to create the technical replicates heatmap
annotation_df <- metadata %>%
  # Create a variable to store the cancer type information
  dplyr::mutate(
    cancer_type = dplyr::case_when(
      startsWith(refinebio_title, "TET2") ~ "TET2",
      startsWith(refinebio_title, "IDH2") ~ "IDH2",
      startsWith(refinebio_title, "WT") ~ "WT",
      TRUE ~ "unknown")
  ) %>%
  # We want to select the variables that we want for annotating the technical
  # replicates heatmap
  dplyr::select(refinebio_accession_code,
                cancer_type,
                refinebio_treatment) %>%
  # The `pheatmap` function requires that the rownames of our annotation object
  # matches the column names of our `DESeaDataSet` object
  tibble::column_to_rownames("refinebio_accession_code")

0.3.6.1 Create annotated heatmap

You can create an annotated heatmap by providing our annotation object to the annotation_col argument of the pheatmap function.

# Create and store the annotated heatmap object
pheatmap_annotated <-
  pheatmap(
    df_by_var,
    cluster_rows = FALSE, # Replace with `TRUE` to cluster heatmap by rows (genes in this case)
    cluster_cols = FALSE, # Replace with `TRUE` to cluster heatmap by columns (samples in this case)
    annotation_col = annotation_df,
    main = "Annotated Heatmap",
    colorRampPalette(c("deepskyblue",
                       "black",
                       "yellow"))(25
                       ),
    scale = "row" # Scale values in the direction of genes (rows)
  )

0.3.7 Save heatmap as a png

You can easily switch this to save to a jpeg or tiff by changing the function and file name within the function to the respective file suffix.

# Open a png file
png(file.path(
  plots_dir,
  "HeatmapSRP070849_annotated.png" # Replace file name with a relevant output plot name
))

# Print your heatmap
pheatmap_annotated

# Close the png file:
dev.off()

0.3.8 Create clustered heatmap and save

You can create a clustered heatmap by telling the pheatmap function to cluster the rows and/or columns.

# Create and store a heatmap object with clustered samples and genes
pheatmap_clustered <-
  pheatmap(
    df_by_var,
    cluster_rows = TRUE, # Replace with `TRUE` to cluster heatmap by rows (genes in this case)
    cluster_cols = TRUE, # Replace with `TRUE` to cluster heatmap by columns (samples in this case)
    annotation_col = annotation_df,
    main = "Clustered Heatmap",
    colorRampPalette(c("deepskyblue",
                       "black",
                       "yellow"))(25
                       ),
    scale = "row" # Scale values in the direction of genes (rows)
  )

Now lets save our clustered heatmap.

# Open a png file
png(file.path(
  plots_dir,
  "HeatmapSRP070849_clustered.png" # Replace file name with a relevant output plot name
))

# Print your heatmap
pheatmap_clustered

# Close the png file:
dev.off()
